Flaws of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this provocative title for his bestseller to draw attention to the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers no longer provide protection easily.
European and American manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals have had to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they talk to may well be in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limits of Friedman's analogy.
As one person put it, the world is not flat, but "uneven."
The contour map of economic activity around the world shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance has not lost its significance either.
Even countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
While Seattle and Vancouver are geographically very close, Vancouver trades far more with the much farther Toronto than with neighboring Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still made an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between continents, which has a history as long as that of human history, witnessing migrations of races and religions, and trade along the ancient Silk Road stretching from medieval Europe to Asia.
But today's globalization is different, developing faster and to a greater extent.
In 1868, when the first transatlantic cable was laid, Europeans and Americans could communicate within just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described a British person in London ordering goods from around the world over the telephone and waiting at home for them to arrive in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British person was an exception among the wealthy.
Today, millions upon millions of people worldwide can buy goods from all around the world in their local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago there was instantaneous global communication, but it exceeded the budget of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into a internet cafe and obtain capabilities that were previously accessible only to governments, multinational corporations, and a few wealthy individuals or institutions with large budgets.
A dramatic drop in computing, communications, and transportation costs has made technology more accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, U.S. Internet users account for less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today, more people than ever before are in possession of information.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were once held only by governments.
Nation-states remain the primary actors in world politics for the time being but must learn to share this vast stage with an increasing number of participants, including organizations like Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Such situations have occurred before.
1914 the world economy was highly integrated, but over the following three decades, economic interdependence among countries continuously decreased.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had seen before, although the Iron Curtain still posed significant barriers.
The First World War was the trigger for this reversal, and during the two world wars and one global cold war, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper problems such as domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic developments, resulting in abnormal ideologies – fascism and communism – which contributed to the fragmentation of nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare state systems in the West wove a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, thereby encouraging them to accept the rewards of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that China's role today is similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving toward nationalism, challenging dominant powers, and ultimately sparking a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
While the US and China’s economies are highly interdependent today, was not Britain and Germany’s economy before 1914 similarly intertwined?
But this reasoning is incomplete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
But even with its current high growth rate, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States for at least two decades.
The greater threat to the Flat World may come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by technological spread.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government's bombing of Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon privatization of war.
If such forces were to obtain nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a complete transformation.
At that time, it would be even more difficult for people and goods to cross national borders.
If such forces were to disrupt the oil output from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's proven oil reserves, a global economic recession similar to the 1930s could further strengthen the power of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
To date, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to remove obstacles.
But the events described above could reverse such policies.
Certain globalization critics might be willing to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst conditions in two areas¾that is, the trend of economic globalization of communication and power could revert, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization could further solidify, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that were the case, the flat world would become a desert.
